    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-03-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-03-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="262"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <head>262. Memorandum From the Director of the Executive Secretariat (<persName
                        corresp="#p_CJA1" type="from">Calhoun</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                        >Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d262fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 737.00/3–1359. Confidential. A handwritten note in the margin reads:
                        “See also attached telegram from Havana.” No telegram is attached to the
                        source text, but the reference may be to telegram 1049 from Havana, March
                        12, summarized in <ref target="#d260fn2">footnote 2, Document
                        260</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-03-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 13, 1959</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">PRESIDENTIAL PARTICIPATION IN <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName> VISIT</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss> is reluctant to recommend at this time on
                    Presidential participation in the <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>
                    visit. Yesterday, for example, Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName> let out another blast at the US,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d262fn2">Not further identified.</note> while on other occasions he
                    has seemed more mellow. The Bureau would prefer to wait, therefore, until
                    perhaps a week or so before April 17 when <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName> is due to address the American Society of Newspaper
                    Editors.</p>
                <p>In view of the widespread domestic American interest in <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>, however, you may think it desirable to
                    apprise the President of your plans with respect to <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName>’s visit and to tell him that we will furnish <pb
                        facs="0463" n="431" xml:id="pg_431"/> recommendations regarding possible
                    Presidential participation at a date closer to <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName>’s arrival, unless the President has some definite ideas
                    of his own at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">John A. Calhoun</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d262fn3">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
